  <page>
    <title>Violin Sonata No. 5 (Beethoven)</title>
    <id>3441</id>
    <revision>
      <id>420619474</id>
      <timestamp>2011-03-25T06:21:15Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>Graham87</username>
        <id>194203</id>
      </contributor>
      <minor />
      <comment>/* External links */ fix link</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">The '''Violin Sonata No. 5''' in [[F major]], Opus 24, is a [[violin sonata]] by [[Ludwig van Beethoven]]. It is often known as the &quot;Spring&quot; sonata (Frühlingssonate), and was published in [[1801 in music|1801]].  Its dedicatee was [[Count Moritz von Fries]], a patron&lt;ref&gt;Fries was also a travelling companion to [[Giovanni Battista Casti]], a playwright and rival of [[Lorenzo da Ponte]], and an influence on [[Mozart]] at a pivotal point in his operatic work, according to [[Alfred Einstein]]'s ''Mozart: His Character, His Work''.&lt;/ref&gt; to whom the [[Violin Sonata No. 4 (Beethoven)|fourth violin sonata]], the [[String Quintet, Op. 29 (Beethoven)|string quintet]] of the same year, and the [[Symphony No. 7 (Beethoven)|seventh symphony]] were also dedicated.

The work is in four movements:

#''[[Allegro (music)|Allegro]]''
#''[[Adagio (music)|Adagio]] molto espressivo''
#''[[Scherzo]]: [[Allegro (music)|Allegro]] molto''
#''[[Rondo]]: [[Allegro (music)|Allegro]] ma non troppo''

The Scherzo and its trio are particularly brief.  The entire sonata takes approximately 22 minutes to perform.

The Allegro movement is featured in stage show [[Fame (musical)|&quot;Fame&quot;]].

