• 3 : [[Glorioso Islands]]
• 4 : [[Juan de Nova Island]]
• 5 : [[Tromelin Island]]
}}
'''Bassas da India''' (also called '''Basse de Judie''') is part of the [[French Southern and Antarctic Lands]]. It is an uninhabited, roughly circular [[atoll]] about {{convert|10|km|0|abbr=on}} in diameter, which corresponds to a total size (including [[lagoon]]) of {{convert|80|km²|0|abbr=on}}.  It is located in the southern [[Mozambique Channel]], about half-way between [[Madagascar]] (which is {{convert|385|km|0|abbr=on}} to the east) and [[Mozambique]], and {{convert|110|km|0|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Europa Island]].  It rises steeply from the [[seabed]] 3000&amp;nbsp;m below.  The reef rim averages around 100&amp;nbsp;m across and completely encloses a shallow lagoon that has a maximum depth of 15&amp;nbsp;m  Its [[Exclusive Economic Zone]] (EEZ) of {{convert|123700|km²|0|abbr=on}} is contiguous with that of [[Europa Island]].

The atoll consists of ten barren rocky islets, with no vegetation, totalling 0.2&amp;nbsp;km² (.077 sq mi) in area.  Those on the north and east sides are 2.1 to 3&amp;nbsp;m high, and those on the west and south sides 1.2&amp;nbsp;m  The reef is completely covered by the sea from 3 hours before to 3 hours after high tide.  The coastline of the reef measures {{convert|35.2|km|0|abbr=on}}.  The region is subject to [[cyclones]].  The atoll has long been a maritime hazard and is the site of numerous [[shipwrecks]].

About 40 and 70&amp;nbsp;km southwest of Bassas da India are [[Jaguar Seamount]] and [[Hall Tablemount]].

__TOC__

